Introduction and dataset description

The aim of this paper is to analyse a dataset and to apply Machine Learning algorithms to produce a reliable result. The object of this study is the dataset Breast Cancer Coimbra taken from UCI Machine Repository containing clinical features of 116 patiens. Clinical features were observed for 64 patients with breast cancer and the reamining 52 who regularly attend healthy controls. Every patient is identified by a list of attirbutes. All the attributes except from the last one are predictors, while the final attribute is the target attribute. We list them below:

  • Age: patient age;

  • BMI: body mass index (kg/m2);

  • Glucose (mg/dL);

  • Insulin (U/mL);

  • HOMA: Homeostasis Model Assessment;

  • Leptin (ng/mL);

  • Adiponectin (µg/mL);

  • Resistin (ng/mL);

  • MCP-1: Monocyte Chemoattractant Protein-1 (pg/dL);

  • Classification: 1 = healthy controls, 2 = breast cancer

The 9 predictors are quantitative, while the response is a binary dependent variable, indicating the precence or absence of breast cancer. The predictors are anthropometric data and parameters which can be gathered in routine blood analysis. Prediction models based on these predictors, if accurate, can potentially be used as a biomarker of breast cancer. The paper’s goal is to produce different models that are able to classify as accurately as possible a patient’s health, given her clinical features.

Classification

In building our classifiers we split the dataset we want to study into two sets. The first one, called training set, contains 81 observations corresponding to the 70% of the whole dataset and it is used to build the different classifiers. The second one, called test or validation set, contains the remaining 35 points of the dataset and it is used to see how the classifiers perform in terms of accuracy on some observations that were not used to build the models. As stated before we will work with 8 predictors instead of 9 since we decided to remove the attribute HOMA.

names(cancer) <- make.names(names(cancer)) 

set.seed(2000)
Samples = sample(1:nrow(cancer),nrow(cancer)*0.7) 
TrainSet = cancer[Samples,-5] 
TestSet = cancer[-Samples,-5]

From the tables and graphs above we notice that observations inside the training set seem to be balanced between the two classes as our original dataset. This makes us believe that we will be able to perform our analysis without too many difficulties.

Logistic regression with Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation

The first technique we use to try to classify our points is called Logistic Regression. This method is applied to classification problems and it aims to predict the probability that an instance belongs to a particular class, given the values of the predictors. In our classification problem we have a binary response variable representing the patient’s health condition that can assume ‘healthy controls’ and ‘breast cancer’ as values. We want to predict the probability that a patient has breast cancer, i.e. that the dependent variable is equal to ‘breast cancer’: in order to keep this probability in the interval \([0,1]\) we need Logistic Regression. This name comes from the fact that the link function of this regression model is the so-called logit function, defined as \(logit(x)=log(\frac{x}{1-x})\). This function forces the probability that the response variable is equal to ‘breast cancer’ to belong to \([0,1]\). If we define \(\pi=\mathbb{P}(Y='breast \quad cancer'| X)\), where \(Y\) represents the Classification attribute and \(X\) represents the array composed by the predictors, then the logistic model can be written as

\(logit(\pi)=log(\frac{\pi}{1-\pi})=\beta_0+\sum_{i=1}^{8}{\beta_iX_i}\)

\(\pi=\frac{exp(\beta_0+\sum_{i=1}^{8}{\beta_iX_i})}{1+exp(\beta_0+\sum_{i=1}^{8}{\beta_iX_i})}\)

where 8 is the number of predictors of our model. In this way we are able to model the conditional distribution of the response variable \(Y\) given the array of 8 predictors \(X\).

In order to select the best possible generalized linear model we use cross-validation: in particular here we fit the model with the technique of leave-one-out cross-validation. There are different methods to perform cross-validation: one method consists in dividing the set that we use to build the model into \(K\) subsets of the same cardinality called folds. At the beginning the first fold is the testing set and the other \(K-1\) folds consitute the training set; then this process is repeated \(K\) times considering at each time a different fold as the testing set. In this way we get \(K\) estimates of the test error and at the end we take the model with the highest accuracy as the final classifier. Some of the most common stategies are given by dividing the training set in 5 folds, 10 folds or \(n\) folds, where \(n\) is the number of observations of the dataset. Here we perform the last one, called leave-one-out cross-validation since a single observation is used for the testing set while the remaining obervations make up the training set. Notice that in our case it is possible to perform LOOCV without having computational problems because we don’t have a lot of observations, but in general it’s easy to understand that performing 5-fold or 10-fold cross-validation is much more feasible.

set.seed(2005)

LOOfit<-train(Classification~., 
               data = TrainSet,
               trControl = trainControl(method = 'LOOCV'),
               method = 'glm',
               family = 'binomial'
               )

The result of this analysis produces the following model:

LDA

Linear Discriminant Analysis is a supervised learning algorithm that helps to find a linear combination of features that separates the two classes of our dataset. The idea of this technique is to find a direction \(v\) and project each sample of the dataset onto the line defined by \(v\) in order to separate as much as possible the two classes of points. This direction \(v\) is called linear discriminant.

In order to be able to classify optimally our points we need to know the posterior distributions, i.e. \(\mathbb{P}(Y=k|X)\), where \(Y=k\) means that the response variable \(Y\) belongs to the class \(k\). If we call \(\pi_k\) the prior probability of belonging to class \(k\) and \(f_k(x)\) is the class-conditional density of \(X\) in class \(Y=k\), then for Bayes theorem we have

\(\mathbb{P}(Y=k|X=x)=\frac{f_k(x)\pi_k}{\sum_{j=1}^{K}{f_j(x)\pi_j}} \quad \forall k=1,\dots,K\)

where \(K\) is the number of classes of the dataset. By hypotesis, each of the classes density must have a Gaussian multivariate distribution

\(f_k(x)=\frac {1}{(2\pi)^{p/2}|\Sigma_k|^{1/2}} \exp(-\frac{1}{2}(x-\mu_k)^T\Sigma_k^{-1}(x-\mu_k)), \quad \forall k=1,\dots,K\)

where \(\mu_k\) and \(\Sigma_k\) are the mean and covariance matrix of class \(k\) points and \(p\) is the number of predictors. Moreover all classes must have the same covariance matrix \(\Sigma_K=\Sigma\). Now we can state that the decision rule: a point is assigned to the class for which the linear discriminant functions

\(\delta_k(x)=x^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k-\frac {1}{2}\mu_k^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k+\log \pi_k\)

is largest. We give to the set where \(\delta_k(x)=\delta_l(x)\) with \(k\) and \(l\) two different classes, the name of decision boundary between the two classes: then, according to the previous equation, this set is linear in \(x\) so it is an hyperplane and it separates the whole space \(\mathbb{R}^p\) into two regions, each of whom contains the points from a single class.

So let’s check if the two assumptions stated above are met in our dataset:

#first assumption: the two groups have the same covariance matrix
group1<- cancer[cancer$Classification=="healthy controls",c(-5,-10)] 
group2<- cancer[cancer$Classification=="breast cancer",c(-5,-10)] 
sigma1=cov(group1)
sigma2=cov(group2) 
norm(sigma1-sigma2, type = "I")
## [1] 69793.15
#second assumption:density of both classes given by a Gaussian multivariate distribution
plot1<-mvn(data = group1, multivariatePlot = "qq")

plot2<-mvn(data = group2, multivariatePlot = "qq")

As we can see from the results obtained, both the assumption are not met. So it is not reasonable to perform LDA because the results obtained would not be reliable.

\(k\)-Nearest Neighbors with Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation

The algorithm of \(k\)-nearest neighbors (\(k\)NN) assumes that observations which are similar are also near to each other. Obviuosly this idea requires a criterion to measure the similarity of two instances of the dataset: this is usually given by the Euclidean distance between points. In order to give to all the features the same weight the dataset needs to be normalized before measuring the distances between different obseravtions. The \(k\)NN method needs a set of observations for which the class is known, again called training set, and an integer \(k\) to be decided before performing the algorithm. For every new point that we want to classify given the vector of features, the algorithm computes the distance between this point and every point of the training set and then it selects the \(k\) points with the smaller distance to it. The new observation is assigned to the class which is more represented among the \(k\) selected points. This algorithm is very useful for datasets that are not too big both in terms of features and instances. The key decision that has to be made before fitting this model is the value of \(k\): since we have a binary classification problem, we take an odd number for \(k\) in order to avoid cases where a point has the same number of class-1 and class-2 neighbors. A small value of \(k\) generates an unstable prediction model, while a large value makes the model computationally heavy. The best way to create an accurate model is to use cross validation to select the proper value of \(k\): this means that we try different values for \(k\) and then chosing the value that maximizes the accuracy of the model.

Also in this case we fit the model by performing the Leave-One-Out cross-validation. In order to understand which is the best value of \(k\) in the \(k\)NN model we use the Leave-One-Out cross-validation for all the odd values of \(k\) between 3 and 15.

set.seed(2058)
kNNModel <- train(TrainSet[,-9], TrainSet[,9],
                  method = "knn",
                  preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                  tuneGrid = expand.grid(k = seq(3,15,2)),
                  trControl = trainControl(method = "LOOCV"), 
                  metric = "Accuracy"
)
kNNModel

So the value of \(k\) that maximizes the accuracy in the Leave-One-Out cross-validation performed is \(k=5\), so we select it to perform a \(k\)NN model and see how it works on the validation set.

kNNpred<- knn(train = TrainSet[,-9], test = TestSet[,-9], cl=TrainSet[,9], k=kappa) 
kNN_table<-table(kNNpred, TestSet[,9], dnn=c("Predicted", "Actual"))
kNN_table
##                   Actual
## Predicted          healthy controls breast cancer
##   healthy controls                6             7
##   breast cancer                   8            14
kNNaccuracy<-sum(diag(kNN_table))/sum(kNN_table)
kNNaccuracy
## [1] 0.5714286

The accuracy of this classifier is about 57% which is rather lower than what we got with logistic regression. This is clear from the table above: just 14 out of 21 patients with breast cancer are correclty classified and just 6 out of 14 healthy patients result having healthy controls. This may be due to the fact that we use 8 predictors and in a quite high-dimensional space the distances between points are not so different. In order to see what happens to the model in a lower-dimensional space we decided to perform a feature extraction with the aim of reducing the dimensionality of our dataset.

PCA

Principal component analysis is an unsupervised learning technique that is used to find the directions along which the data have the maximum variance: these directions are normalized linear combinations of the variables with highest variance. Once the features related to these directions are found, the others can be ignored while losing small information about the dataset, as the data have small variance along the ignored directions. The orthogonal axes (principal components) of the new subspace can be interpreted as the directions in which there is maximum variance with the constraint that the axes must be orthogonal. This method is useful to make the dataset easier to understand, especially in classification problems. So we perform PCA in order to uderstand if the result we obtain with a model with less variables is comparable with the one with all the variables. In order to compute the new axis of the subspace, PCA works with the standard deviation of each variable: variables with high standard deviation have more influence in the computation of the axis with respect to those who have smaller standard deviation. So before performing PCA, since our variables are not all measured in the same unit we need to center and scale our data in order to have every variable with the same influence weight. The R function prcomp performs PCA to our dataset (ignoring the classifier) after centering and scaling our data.

PCA = prcomp(cancer[c(-5,-10)], center = T, scale. = T)

After the standardization the distribution of every attirbute changes as shown below.

df <- as.data.frame(cancer[c(-5,-10)])
dfs <- stack(df)
plot1 <- ggplot(dfs, aes (x=values)) +
  geom_density(aes(group=ind, colour=ind)) + theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + ggtitle("Before standardization")

df2 <- as.data.frame(scale(cancer[c(-5,-10)], center = TRUE, scale = TRUE)) 
dfs2 <- stack(df2)
plot2 <- ggplot(dfs2, aes (x=values)) +
  geom_density(aes(group=ind, colour=ind)) + theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") + ggtitle("After standardization")

ggarrange(plot1, plot2, ncol=2, nrow=1, common.legend = TRUE, legend="bottom")

We get 8 principal components, since the dataset has 8 predictors: each of these components contains the explanation of a certain proportion of the variance of the dataset. The summary shows that the first principal component explains almost the 31% of the total variation of the dataset, while the first two principal components together explain almost the 46% as the second one overcomes the 15%. It is sufficient to consider the first 5 principal components to overtake the level of 80% of the variance, or the first 6 to exceed the 91%. We can see this with two plots: on the left we plot how the proportion of variance decreases when we pass from a principal component to the following one and on the right we plot how cumulative proportion of variance increases when adding another principal component to the previous ones.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(summary(PCA)$importance["Proportion of Variance",], type="b", lwd=2, lty=1, xlab = "Index of component", ylab = "Proportion of Variance") 
plot(summary(PCA)$importance["Cumulative Proportion",], type="b", lwd=2, lty=1, xlab = "Index of component", ylab = "Cumulative Proportion")

par(mfrow=c(1,1))

Now we plot a graph that provides the best two-dimensional approximation to the observations in our dataset, since we use as axes the first two principal components. We will also be able to see where the observations are placed with respect to the loading vectors.

par(mar=c(4,2,2,2), mgp=c(1,0.2,0))
biplot(PCA,choices=c(1,2), xlabs = rep("", nrow(cancer)))

The more the features are located close to each other, the more they are related with each other. For example, BMI, MCP-1 and Resistin seem to be quite related. It is also possible to observe that patients with high levels of Insulin and Glucose will probably be classified into the breast cancer class.

The accuracy reaches the 77.1% so we get a big improvement in terms of accuracy by reducing the dimesion of the predictors’ space: this shows clearly that \(k\)NN performs better when we do not have too many features. We can notice a big improvement also in the predicitons: now 17 out of 21 patients with breast cancer are correclty classified and 10 out of 14 healthy patients result having healthy controls (remember that 1 stands for ‘healthy controls’ and 2 stands for ‘breast cancer’).

Decision Tree

A quite simple method for classification is the Decision Tree, where the main idea is to split the space of the features into a number of simple non-overlapping regions and to assign each new observation to the most commonly occuring class (the mode class) of the training observations in its region. The name of this technique comes from the fact that the rules that divide the whole space into many regions can be represented as a tree. A decision tree is characterized by:

  • the internal nodes which are the points along the tree where the predictor space is split into a binary partition after a test on a single feature (the first node is called root node);
  • the branches which connect two nodes and represent the two possible outcomes of the test on an internal node;
  • the leaves or terminal nodes which are the final regions of the partition.

This method has a top-down approach beacuse the algorithm starts from the whole attributes’ space and then it is split with a binary partition represented by two new branches that move away from the root. The algorithm is also considered greedy because in the tree-building process the splits are not picked in order to get the best possible tree in term of accuracy, but each split is the best possible at that particular step of the algorithm. In order to build this classifier we need some criteria to construct the regions: of course we want the classification error to be as small as possible. We define

\(\hat{p}_{mk} =\frac{1}{N_m}\sum_{x_i\in R_m}{\mathbb{I}(y_i=k)}\)

\(k(m)=\arg\max_k \hat{p}_{km}\)

respectively as the proportion of class \(k\) observations in the \(m\)-th region of the partition of the whole space and as the most frequent class in the \(m\)-th region. Then for each region we have the so-called classification error rate, defined as \(E=1-\hat{p}_{mk(m)}\), that is defined as the fraction of the training observations in the region that do not belong to the most common class of that region. At each step of the tree-building process, the algorithm selects the best split in terms of minimizion of \(E\). Anyway this is not sufficiently sensitive for tree-growing, so there are two other indeces that are usually preferred to it.

  • Gini index \(G=\sum_{k=1}^{K}{\hat{p}_{mk}(1-\hat{p}_{mk})}\) that is a measure of total variance across all the \(K\) classes: it becomes smaller as \(\hat{p}_{mk}\) gets close to \(0\) or \(1\).
  • Cross entropy or deviance \(D=-\sum_{k=1}^{K}{\hat{p}_{mk}\log\hat{p}_{mk}}\) that is numerically similar but alternative to Gini index.

A small value for \(G\) or \(D\) in a certain region of the partition means that the considered region contains predominantly observations of the same class.

It is quite common that the accuracy of a decision tree is not really high if compared to other classifiers because this model has the problem of overfitting: this classifier adapts too much to the dataset so it is not very performing on the test set that contains different observations. A way to reduce the risk of overfitting is to prune the tree: this technique aims to reduce the size of the learning tree without losing in accuracy. The idea is to build an initial tree where each leaf contains a small number of observations (even just one) and then removing the nodes of the tree that do not provide a notable information for classification. Anyway if we fit the decision tree as described, even with pruning, it is quite common to get a model which is worse in terms of accuracy.

Now we fit a decision tree for our classification problem: here we use the 5-folds cross-validation to tune the parameter which represents the maximum allowed depth for our tree model. The rpart function fits a decision tree with recursive partitioning using the Gini index for the splits.

Bagging and Random Forest

One of the most common methods to improve the decision tree model is performing a random forest. This approach, along with boosting, uses trees as blocks to build a more powerful classifier which does not overfit the training data. The random forest algorithm applies the technique of bagging to tree learners. Bagging method consists in generating \(B\) different bootstrapped training datasets from the original one, by repeatedly sampling at random from it (with replacement); then a classifier is built on every dataset and the final classifier is obtained as the average of the classifiers. As we are considering a classification problem we record the class predicted by every single classifier of the model and at the end the final prediction at point \(x\) is given by the most common class among the \(B\) different predictions at \(x\) (this is called the majority vote). This approach guarantees an improvement in terms of accuracy in comparison with a single tree, but clearly it is computationally heavier. The test error for a bagged model is evaluated with the out-of-bag (OOB) error. Each tree of the model uses about two-thirds of the total observations of the dataset: we call out-of-bag observations those not used to build the tree. The predicted class of an observation is obtained by taking the majority vote for that observation between the trees in which that instance is OOB. This technique is consider equivalent to the Leave-One-Out cross-validation and it estimates the error for the bagged model.

The main idea of random forest is to go beyond bagging in order to decorrelate the trees of the model: each time we have to split the attributes’ space, the model picks randomly a subset of \(m\) features and then the division is made considering the selected features only. This process is repeated for any split of any tree of the random forest. A typical choice for the value of \(m\) is \(m\approx \sqrt{p}\), where \(p\) is the number of predictors in the dataset. This technique of using different sets of predictors for different splits decorrelates the trees, so that the final model has a small variance if compared to a single decision tree method.

The randomForest function of R requires different parameters to be set: the number of trees (ntree), the number \(m\) of predictors to be considered at each split (mtry), the maximum number of leaves for a single tree (maxnodes) and many others. In order to build the best possible random forest model with respect to ntree, mtry and maxnodes, we first fit the model with the default values of these parameters and then we tune them one at a time.

Support Vector Machine

Support vector machine (SVM) is one of the most recent and performing approaches in classification problems: this method is a more complex version of the maximal margin vector classifier and linear support vector classifier. The main difference is the fact that the decision boudaries are no more linear as in those two classifiers: in such situations the predictors’ space is enlarged through non linear functions of the features. A typical example is using quadratic, cubic, polynomial transformations: for example it is possible to build a classifier which does not consider only the original \(p\) features \(x_1,\dots,x_p\) but it uses \(2p\) attributes \(x_1,x_1^2,\dots,x_p,x_p^2\). So the main idea of the support vector machine is to enlarge the features space in order to build a classifier which is suitable for non linear decision boundaries: the functions that are used to enlarge the space are called kernels and they can have very different expressions. It can be demonstrated that the linear support vector classifier can be found by computing inner products only: in the SVM kernels measure the similarity of two observations and they replace the inner product. Some kernels (represented with the letter \(K\)) are:

  • linear kernel \(K(x_i,x_{i'})=\sum_{j=1}^{p}{x_{ij}x_{i'j}}\), which is the simple inner product and it uses Pearson standard correlation to quantify the similarity of two instances;
  • polynomial kernel (of degree \(d\in\mathbb{N}\)) \(K(x_i,x_{i'})=(1+\sum_{j=1}^{p}{x_{ij}x_{i'j}})^d\), which is used with \(d>1\) and it builds flexible decision boudaries by fitting a support vector classifier in a higher-dimensional feature space than the original one;
  • radial kernel \(K(x_i,x_{i'})=\exp (-\gamma\sum_{j=1}^{p}{(x_{ij}-x_{i'j})^2)}\), with \(\gamma>0\), whose basic idea is that in classifying \(\bar{x}\) we give no weight to those observations that are far from \(\bar{x}\): in this sense the radial kernel has very local behaviour.

Here we perform the radial SVM using the same 5 folds we used to do cross-validation in building the random forest in order to have a good comparison of the two models, since these two are probably the best models we can perform on a binary classification problem.

Conclusions

As we already observed, SVM is the best model due to both computational speed and accuracy, followed by the logistic regression. But to have a more clear situation of the models we built, let’s have a look to ROC curves and AUC. The Receiving Operator Characteristic (ROC) is an operator that evaluates the goodness of a method using different statistics on the axis while AUC stands for Area Under the Curve: higher values of the AUC correspond to better models. In our case the statistics used for the ROC representation are:

  • sensitivity: \[\begin{equation} \frac{TP}{TP+FN} \end{equation}\]
  • specificity: \[\begin{equation} \frac{TN}{FP+TN} \end{equation}\]
Notice that the accuracy we computed at the end of every model is given by \[\begin{equation} \frac{TP+TN}{TP+FP+TN+FN} \end{equation}\]

Before plotting the ROC curves and the repsective AUC, we also introduce the F1 score that allows us to understand better how the classification worked in each model:

\[\begin{equation} F1 score = \frac{2}{\frac{1}{S}+\frac{1}{P}} \end{equation}\] where \[\begin{equation} Precision = P = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} \end{equation}\]

and S stands for sensitivity.
